\subsection{Overview and Relevance}
Generative artificial intelligence has achieved significant advancements with the introduction of diffusion models, proving their capability in producing diverse and high-quality outputs across various modalities such as image, text, and audio. These models provide critical tools for multiple applications, including creative design, synthetic data generation, and predictive analysis. Despite their growing importance, concerns surrounding the potential for memorization of sensitive information during training pose ethical challenges regarding data privacy and responsible AI deployment. To address these issues, innovative methodologies are required to enhance model performance while ensuring compliance with data confidentiality standards.

\subsection{Addressing Technical Challenges}
Mitigating the memorization phenomenon in diffusion models demands overcoming considerable challenges. These include the capacity to distinguish learned general patterns from memorized instances and adapt training processes to reduce susceptibility to such behavior without compromising generative fidelity. Computational cost and scalability also emerge as critical considerations, emphasizing the need for solutions that balance efficiency and effectiveness. This domain calls for concerted effort in developing novel approaches capable of dynamically identifying high memorization risk scenarios and modulating model updates accordingly.

\subsection{Contribution of D-DAME}
This work introduces the Dynamic Discriminative Anti-Memorization Ensemble (D-DAME) framework, a novel approach integrating ensemble strategies with adaptive feedback mechanisms to address memorization challenges in diffusion models. The main contributions include:
\begin{itemize}
\item Developing a Discriminative Memory Risk Estimator (DMRE) for dynamic identification of memorization-prone samples using attention mechanisms.
\item Implementing adaptive gradient modulation strategies to balance training adjustments based on sample risk scores.
\item Validating the framework through comprehensive experiments, demonstrating its efficacy in reducing memorization while maintaining generative quality.
\item Benchmarking D-DAME's advancements against existing methodologies, showcasing its role in advancing ethical AI practices.
\end{itemize}
The subsequent sections elaborate on the theoretical formulation, experimental validation, and observed outcomes of the proposed framework.

