\subsection{Dataset Description and Preprocessing}

This section outlines the datasets utilized for the experiments and the preprocessing techniques applied to prepare the data for the proposed D-DAME framework.

\subsubsection{Datasets}

The following datasets were employed based on their relevance to the tasks of image synthesis and memorization analysis:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{CIFAR-10}~\cite{krizhevsky2009learning}: Comprising 60,000 labeled images categorized into ten classes, serving as a benchmark for standard classification and synthesis evaluations.
    \item \textbf{CIFAR-100}~\cite{krizhevsky2009learning}: An extension of CIFAR-10 with 100 distinct classes, allowing for fine-grained analysis of generative performance.
    \item \textbf{AFHQ-DOG}~\cite{choi2020starganv2}: A subset of the AFHQ dataset focused on high-quality canine image synthesis, tailored to assess unconditional generation tasks.
    \item \textbf{LAION-10k}: A representative subset derived from the LAION-400M dataset~\cite{schuhmann2021laion}, containing 10,000 image-text pairs, ideal for evaluating text-conditioned generation models.
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{Data Preprocessing}

Preprocessing steps were systematically implemented to ensure data uniformity and compatibility with the experimental setup:

\begin{itemize}
    \item Resizing: Image dimensions were standardized, with CIFAR datasets resized to $32 \times 32$ pixels and AFHQ-DOG images to $256 \times 256$ pixels.
    \item Augmentation: Random horizontal flips were applied during training to enhance model robustness and mitigate overfitting.
    \item Normalization: Pixel values were normalized within each channel to achieve zero mean and unit variance, aligning with standard preprocessing practices.
\end{itemize}

The diligent curation and preprocessing of datasets establish a consistent foundation for evaluating the performance and robustness of the proposed methodology.

