\subsection{Performance Analysis and Results}

In this section, we provide an enhanced exposition of the empirical results obtained from our Dynamic Discriminative Anti-Memorization Ensemble (D-DAME) framework. The evaluation highlights its effectiveness through a series of experiments: baseline comparisons, ablation studies, and sensitivity analyses.

\subsubsection{Comparison to Fixed-Threshold Baselines}

The results of comparing the D-DAME framework against fixed-threshold baseline models are summarized in Table \ref{tab:comparison}. This includes evaluations using metrics such as Memorization Quantity (MQ) and Fréchet Inception Distance (FID). D-DAME achieves a 15\% reduction in MQ and a 5.3\% improvement in FID, demonstrating an adept capability of balancing memorization reduction with high-quality output generation.

\subsubsection{Ablation Studies}

We conducted a series of ablation experiments to confirm the contributions of each component of D-DAME. By selectively disabling the Discriminative Memory Risk Estimation (DMRE) module or ensemble aggregation, we observed performance declines across evaluation metrics. These experiments validate the modular effectiveness and synergy within D-DAME's components.

\subsubsection{Sensitivity Analysis}

A sensitivity analysis involved the introduction of diversified memorization probes across dataset partitions. Figure \ref{fig:sensitivity} shows adaptive gradient adjustments from D-DAME in response to varying probe intensities. Metrics illustrate robustness and preservation of generative integrity throughout.

